Hardware you are having an issue with: in my case, phototransistors
Version of Johnny-Five: 1.1.0
What your expectations are: Sensor.Digital.on('change') callback called as fast as possible
What the actual outcome is: on very rapid events firing, lots of callback calls are lost
Steps to reproduce (including code samples):

- connect phototransistor (in my case, a TEMT6000) to digital pin 6, 5v, and ground
- point a laser LED to it
- place a USB fan between the laser and the phototransistor (or something that can fire events at like 100hz)

Run the following code

```
var five = require("johnny-five"),
  board = new five.Board(),
  i = 0;

board.on("ready", function() {
  sensor1 = new five.Sensor.Digital({pin: 6, freq: 1});
  sensor1.on("change", function(val) {
    if (val == 0) {
      console.log(i++);
    }
  });
});
```

This one will show very slow readings.

```
var five = require("johnny-five"),
  board = new five.Board(),
  i = 0;

board.on("ready", function() {
  this.samplingInterval(1);
  this.pinMode(6, five.Pin.INPUT);
  this.digitalRead(6, function(val) {
    if (val == 0) {
      console.log(i++);
    }
  });
});
```

This one will be way faster.

Looks like there's some overhead when using the Sensor.Digital class. I haven't dived into the code a lot, but the Sensor class code fires the digital events first and then returns immediately if type == 'digital' so I don't think the problem is there.

